<dl id="n26268c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n26" href="#n26268c">N26 (VI.B.18)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n26all.htm#n26268c"> 268(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ nuncupatory words <small>Green</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n26268c"><li>FW 432.10 </li><li><a href="../../flex/qA/lexqA.htm#n26268c">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/qA/l39qA.htm#n26268c">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n26268c">MS VI.F.6-3</ms> </li><li>JJA not reproduced <a name="qAd10dash" href="../../FF/fdra/qda.htm#qAd10dash">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/qA/qAd10.htm#n26268c">Draft: III&sect;2A.10</a>'</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[Institutions of the Private Law. Plebian family]</font>&mdash;Even to those of a non-Latin race <font color="green">[plebs: Etruscans, Greeks, &amp;c]</font> <i>manus</i> over their wives and <i>potestas</i> over their children would become a desideratum. <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> Though the plebians seem to have always been excluded from confarreation <font color="green">[lawful marriage]</font> <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> two civil modes of acquiring marital <i>manus</i> were available to them after they had obtained citizenship, viz. <i>coemptio</i> and <i>usus</i>. <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> <i>Coemptio</i> was just a simple adaptation of mancipation above referred to. It was, as we may infer from what we know of it at a later time, a sale of the woman to the man <i>per aes et libram</i> for a nominal price. The price being fictitious, a piece of copper (<i>raudusculum</i>) was used to represent it, and this was handed over to the seller, who would ordinarily be the woman&apos;s <i>paterfamilias</i>, or, if she were <i>sui juris</i>, her gentile tutor. The <mark>nuncupatory words</mark> used in the ceremony have unfortunately not been preserved &hellip; <small> &ldquo;ROMAN LAW&rdquo; <a name="EBRL2" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#EBRL2"><cite title="source">Encyclopaedia Britannica</cite></a>, 11th edit. (1911) 530</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
